<sn><md>### Biological Efficiency of Aerobic Respiration

* **ATP produced:** 36–38 ATP (average considered = 38 ATP)

* **Energy captured:**
  $$
  38 \text{ ATP} \times 7.3 \text{ kcal per ATP} = 277.4 \text{ kcal}
  $$

* **Efficiency:**
  $$
  \frac{277.4}{686} \times 100 \approx 40%
  $$

✔ **Aerobic respiration efficiency ≈ 40%**
(remaining 60% lost as heat)
</md></sn><sn><md>### Biological Efficiency of Anaerobic Respiration

* **ATP produced:** Only **2 ATP**

* **Energy captured:**
  $$
  2 \text{ ATP} \times 7.3 \text{ kcal per ATP} = 14.6 \text{ kcal}
  $$

* **Efficiency:**
  $$
  \frac{14.6}{686} \times 100 \approx 2%
  $$

✔ **Anaerobic respiration efficiency ≈ 2%**
(very low because most energy remains in lactic acid/ethanol)
</md></sn><sn><md>### Table: Aerobic vs Anaerobic Respiration

| **Feature**                | **Aerobic Respiration**                      | **Anaerobic Respiration**                    |
| -------------------------- | -------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------- |
| **Oxygen Requirement**     | Requires oxygen                              | Occurs without oxygen                        |
| **Location**               | Mitochondria                                 | Cytoplasm                                    |
| **Number of ATP Produced** | 36–38 ATP                                    | 2 ATP                                        |
| **End Products**           | CO₂ + H₂O                                    | Lactic acid (animals), Ethanol + CO₂ (yeast) |
| **Biological Efficiency**  | ~40%                                         | ~2%                                          |
| **Pathway Involved**       | Glycolysis → Acetyl Co-A → Krebs Cycle → ETS | Glycolysis → Fermentation                    |
| **Energy Release**         | High                                         | Very low                                     |
| **Organisms**              | Plants, animals, aerobic microbes            | Yeast, bacteria, muscle cells under low O₂   |
| **By-products**            | Non-toxic                                    | Often toxic (lactic acid, ethanol)           |
